WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.570 --> 00:00:07.900
- Good afternoon, everyone.

00:00:07.900 --> 00:00:08.770
I'm Liz Cohen.

00:00:08.770 --> 00:00:11.130
I'm Dean of the Radcliffe
Institute for Advanced Study,

00:00:11.130 --> 00:00:14.520
and it is a pleasure to
welcome you to today's lecture

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:17.340
by Professor Michael Kazin.

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:21.840
Here at Radcliffe we are
dedicated to promoting

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:25.780
new research and inquiry, and
we bring leading scholars,

00:00:25.780 --> 00:00:28.710
scientists, artists,
and public intellectuals

00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:32.100
from all of Harvard's schools,
and from around the world,

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:34.110
to share their work
with each other

00:00:34.110 --> 00:00:38.340
and with broad interested
public like you.

00:00:38.340 --> 00:00:41.880
Today's talk is part of
our Davis Lecture Series,

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:44.100
established by Kim
and Judy Davis,

00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:46.770
to bring prominent
thinkers in all fields

00:00:46.770 --> 00:00:49.570
here to Radcliffe
for public talks.

00:00:49.570 --> 00:00:53.530
I am so glad to see Kim and
Judy here with us today.

00:00:53.530 --> 00:00:56.400
And I'm grateful to them
for their generous support

00:00:56.400 --> 00:00:58.320
of the Institute.

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:02.310
Now, today our speaker is
Professor Michael Kazin, who

00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:05.880
will enlighten us on the
very important topic of,

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:08.550
does the left have a future?

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:12.360
Mike is uniquely qualified
to tackle this question,

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:15.960
because he is a rare historian
who is just as engaged

00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:22.290
in contemporary politics, as he
is in the politics of the past.

00:01:22.290 --> 00:01:26.400
Almost exactly one
year ago today,

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:29.820
the presidential
election of 2016

00:01:29.820 --> 00:01:33.840
caused many Americans, on
both the left and the right,

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:37.650
to question their assumptions
about American politics.

00:01:37.650 --> 00:01:40.470
Even before election
day, the campaign

00:01:40.470 --> 00:01:43.590
revealed deep
divisions, not only

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:46.710
between blue and red
voters, but within

00:01:46.710 --> 00:01:50.910
the Democratic and Republican
parties themselves.

00:01:50.910 --> 00:01:53.070
There are many examples
that illustrate

00:01:53.070 --> 00:01:55.020
these intraparty divides.

00:01:55.020 --> 00:01:59.310
But I will remind you of just
one telling anecdote related

00:01:59.310 --> 00:02:01.560
to the Democratic Party.

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:04.740
Only hours before the
Democratic National Convention

00:02:04.740 --> 00:02:08.070
opened last summer,
Senator Bernie Sanders

00:02:08.070 --> 00:02:10.410
spoke to a crowd
of his supporters,

00:02:10.410 --> 00:02:13.890
calling on them to support the
party's presumptive nominee

00:02:13.890 --> 00:02:16.710
for president, Hillary
Rodham Clinton.

00:02:16.710 --> 00:02:20.070
Sanders's words were met
with such loud booing

00:02:20.070 --> 00:02:22.320
that he was forced
to stop speaking,

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:25.530
and then adamantly
insist and I quote him,

00:02:25.530 --> 00:02:29.460
"This is the real world
that we live in," end quote.

00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:33.570
That particular moment spoke
to a dilemma and a divide

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:36.300
that would continue to
plague the Democrats

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:39.270
throughout the fall's
presidential campaign,

00:02:39.270 --> 00:02:42.150
and that persists as
the party prepares

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:46.350
for the next presidential
contest in 2020.

00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:48.150
Under a Trump
administration, it's

00:02:48.150 --> 00:02:52.320
clear what the left
is advocating against.

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:56.280
But what, if anything,
unites a disparate opposition

00:02:56.280 --> 00:02:58.950
that spans from
moderate liberals

00:02:58.950 --> 00:03:01.080
to farther left
and populist wings.

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:06.690
How wide a tent can left-leaning
challengers gather under?

00:03:06.690 --> 00:03:09.150
What should they advocate for?

00:03:09.150 --> 00:03:11.970
And what should
their next steps be?

00:03:11.970 --> 00:03:15.090
These questions are likely
what brought so many of you

00:03:15.090 --> 00:03:16.290
here today.

00:03:16.290 --> 00:03:20.400
And you may feel that you and
other like minded Americans

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:22.740
are facing an
historic crisis that

00:03:22.740 --> 00:03:25.800
calls for brand new answers.

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:29.790
Or maybe you like the
direction the country is going,

00:03:29.790 --> 00:03:33.180
and you are here to learn how
to ensure that the left does not

00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:35.820
have a future.

00:03:35.820 --> 00:03:39.720
Either way, I imagine that we
will learn from Mike today that

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:43.320
it is far from the first
time that the left--

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:45.090
or the right for that matter--

00:03:45.090 --> 00:03:49.980
has fragmented, grappled with
challenging internal divisions,

00:03:49.980 --> 00:03:52.740
and had its future
survival questioned.

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:55.950
Let me just offer two
historical precedents.

00:03:55.950 --> 00:03:59.940
In 1948, Henry Wallace and
his Progressive Party split

00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:03.510
with the Democrats, led by
then President Harry S. Truman,

00:04:03.510 --> 00:04:07.020
and advocated for national
health insurance and expansion

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:09.810
of the social safety
net, as well as greater

00:04:09.810 --> 00:04:13.680
racial desegregation and a more
conciliatory foreign policy,

00:04:13.680 --> 00:04:15.690
among other issues.

00:04:15.690 --> 00:04:19.440
In that same election, then
South Carolina Governor Strom

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:22.520
Thurmond, and his
segregationist Dixiecrats,

00:04:22.520 --> 00:04:26.590
challenged Truman and Republican
candidate Thomas F. Dewey

00:04:26.590 --> 00:04:28.370
from the right.

00:04:28.370 --> 00:04:33.260
Two decades later, in 1968,
profound divisions again

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:35.600
emerge within the
Democratic Party

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:37.880
when President Lyndon
Baines Johnson, and later

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:40.190
his vice president
Hubert Humphrey,

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:43.400
were challenged on the left,
first by Minnesota Senator

00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:47.150
Eugene McCarthy, and then also
by New York Senator Robert

00:04:47.150 --> 00:04:48.290
Kennedy.

00:04:48.290 --> 00:04:51.210
And interestingly in
that same election,

00:04:51.210 --> 00:04:53.540
George Wallace, a former
Democratic governor

00:04:53.540 --> 00:04:56.840
from Alabama, mobilized
significant support

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:00.290
from southern and blue
collar Northern Democrats

00:05:00.290 --> 00:05:03.920
for his third party
candidacy for president.

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:09.260
With eerie echoes of today,
Time Magazine in October 1968,

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:12.570
described Wallace's
supporters as, and I quote,

00:05:12.570 --> 00:05:15.410
"a coalition of
frustration, " end quote,

00:05:15.410 --> 00:05:18.140
who refuse to believe what
they read in the newspapers

00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:19.370
and magazines.

00:05:19.370 --> 00:05:22.970
Wallace himself actively
stirred up racial animus,

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:25.940
and frequently railed against
government bureaucrats,

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:28.970
intellectuals, and the press.

00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:32.660
I hope I have made my point
that historical perspective can

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:35.720
be helpful in understanding
the complexities

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:38.210
of our current political moment.

00:05:38.210 --> 00:05:42.290
I say this, not in
support of the old cliche

00:05:42.290 --> 00:05:45.170
that history repeats
itself, but because history

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:49.940
can suggest new questions and
encourage rigorous analysis.

00:05:49.940 --> 00:05:52.670
With that goal in mind,
I am delighted to welcome

00:05:52.670 --> 00:05:56.090
Michael Kazin to the
Radcliffe Institute today.

00:05:56.090 --> 00:05:58.764
Mike is a leading historian
of the American left.

00:05:58.764 --> 00:06:00.680
He is a professor in the
Department of History

00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:02.960
at Georgetown
University, as well as

00:06:02.960 --> 00:06:05.570
the editor of Dissent,
a magazine that

00:06:05.570 --> 00:06:08.240
has been influencing
American political thought

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:11.660
since its first issue in 1954.

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:15.740
Under Mike's leadership, Dissent
has aggressively reached out

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:19.400
to new audiences,
particularly younger ones,

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:21.620
and it is now
addressing a wide range

00:06:21.620 --> 00:06:24.260
of issues relevant to them.

00:06:24.260 --> 00:06:26.690
Dissent magazine under
Mike's leadership

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:29.150
may, in fact, have
some important lessons

00:06:29.150 --> 00:06:32.300
to teach the American left
as it seeks to redefine

00:06:32.300 --> 00:06:35.540
itself and secure a future.

00:06:35.540 --> 00:06:39.410
Mike is renowned for his
extensive research and writing.

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:42.830
One theme that ties his
wide-ranging body of work

00:06:42.830 --> 00:06:46.280
together, is attention
to uncovering

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:50.300
the coherent ideology of
both the left and the right,

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:54.170
powerfully reminding
us that ideas, not just

00:06:54.170 --> 00:06:58.520
interests, matter in American
politics and political history.

00:06:58.520 --> 00:07:01.850
Mike is the author or
editor of 10 books.

00:07:01.850 --> 00:07:04.970
He's especially well-known
for The Populous Persuasion,

00:07:04.970 --> 00:07:08.840
An American History, as
well as America Divided,

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:11.990
The Civil War of the
1960s, which he coauthored

00:07:11.990 --> 00:07:13.730
with Maurice Isserman.

00:07:13.730 --> 00:07:16.760
Mike's most recent book
entitled War Against War,

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:20.930
The American Fight for
Peace, 1914 - 1918,

00:07:20.930 --> 00:07:24.680
examines the often forgotten
resistance to the United States

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:28.670
entering World War I. And he
is now at work on a new book

00:07:28.670 --> 00:07:33.890
entitled, Making Democrats, From
Andrew Jackson to Barack Obama

00:07:33.890 --> 00:07:35.430
and Beyond.

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:37.880
So here's how this
afternoon will work.

00:07:37.880 --> 00:07:40.010
Mike will deliver his
lecture, and there

00:07:40.010 --> 00:07:43.940
will be time for brief Q&amp;A.
We will put a microphone

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:45.050
in the center aisle.

00:07:45.050 --> 00:07:48.200
And if you would like to ask
a question, please come up,

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:51.800
identify yourself, and
then ask your question.

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:53.930
After the final
question, I invite

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:57.530
you to join us for a reception
next door in the Sheerr Room

00:07:57.530 --> 00:07:59.840
on the first floor of Fay House.

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:03.810
Now, please join me in giving a
warm welcome to Michael Kazin.

